Art, architecture, math, science—and above all, faith 🪷🤍
These 4 magnificent caves were carved between the 6th and 8th century CE.
Can’t help but bow down to the brilliance of our ancestors 🙏
.
The Badami Caves were built between the 6th and 8th centuries CE during the rule of the Early Chalukya dynasty, particularly under King Mangalesha and Pulakeshin I and II.

Here’s a quick breakdown:
	•	Cave 1 (Hindu – Shaivite): Around 578 CE, dedicated to Lord Shiva.
	•	Cave 2 (Hindu – Vaishnavite): Around early 6th century, dedicated to Lord Vishnu.
	•	Cave 3 (Hindu – Vaishnavite): Dated 578 CE, known for its intricate Vishnu carvings, believed to have been commissioned by Mangalesha.
	•	Cave 4 (Jain): Built slightly later, around 7th to early 8th century CE, dedicated to Jain Tirthankaras, possibly during the reign of Later Chalukyas.

These caves showcase a remarkable blend of Dravidian architecture and rock-cut artistry, making them among the earliest and finest examples of Indian cave temple design.
